### Step 2: Suppress Console Outputs in Production (Recommended)
You can intercept and mute all frontend `console` prints in a production environment so that users and attackers cannot inspect logs through their browser consoles.

Add a simple initialization script to [base.html:L1246](file:///c:/BatchHost-Pro/templates/base.html#L1246) (inside the main script block):

```javascript
// Automatically disable all console statements in production environments
if (window.location.hostname !== '172.100.31.40' && window.location.hostname !== '172.100.31.40') {
    console.log = function() {};
    console.error = function() {};
    console.warn = function() {};
    console.info = function() {};
}
```

---

### Step 3: Implement Centralized Client-Side Error Logging (Optional)
If you still need visibility into client-side errors without displaying them to the user, you can create a simple API endpoint in Flask `/api/log_error` and write client-side script errors to the server log instead of printing them locally:

```javascript
window.onerror = function (message, source, lineno, colno, error) {
    // Send Javascript error to the server for secure logging
    fetch('/api/log_error', {
        method: 'POST',
        headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },
        body: JSON.stringify({ message, source, lineno, colno })
    });
    return true; // Prevents the fire of standard browser error message in console
};
```

